# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: econometrics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:econometrics/econometrics] A basic tool for econometrics is the multiple linear regression model.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] *Econometric theory* uses statistical theory and mathematical statistics to evaluate and develop econometric methods.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Econometricians try to find estimators that have desirable statistical properties including unbiasedness, efficiency, and consistency.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] *Applied econometrics* uses theoretical econometrics and real-world data for assessing economic theories, developing econometric models, analysing economic history, and forecasting.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The origins of econometrics can be traced to the development of the least squares method in the early nineteenth century.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Initially applied in astronomy and geodesy to estimate celestial motions and other physical phenomena, least squares later became a foundational technique in regression analysis.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The development of statistical and econometric methods was influenced by earlier contributions to political arithmetic and quantitative social inquiry by figures such as Gregory King, Francis Ysidro Edgeworth, Vilfredo Pareto, and Sir William Petty.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Early econometric research was exemplified by works such as Henry Ludwell Moore's *Synthetic Economics*.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] As statistical applications expanded to classification problems, linear discriminant analysis (LDA) was introduced in 1936 to predict categorical outcomes.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Logistic regression emerged during the 1940s as an alternative approach for modeling binary outcomes.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] In the early 1970s, the generalized linear model (GLM) framework was developed, unifying linear and logistic regression within a broader class of statistical models.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Throughout much of the twentieth century, statistical learning methods were predominantly linear because non-linear techniques were computationally demanding.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Improvements in computing power during the 1980s facilitated the development and adoption of non-linear approaches, including classification and regression trees (CART), generalized additive models (GAMs), and artificial neural networks.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] During the 1990s, support vector machines (SVMs) emerged as another important class of predictive models.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] In modern econometrics, other statistical tools are frequently used, but linear regression is still the most frequently used starting point for an analysis.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Estimating a linear regression on two variables can be visualized as fitting a line through data points representing paired values of the independent and dependent variables.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] One of the earliest uses of linear regression was in 1889 by British statistician Udny Yule.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Yule was seeking to causally identify a relationship between public assistance and the number of impoverished people in England.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Using two time periods from the 1871 and 1881 census data at the county level, he estimated the effect of receiving social assistance on the rate of poverty.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Another example, one that is rarely used today, can be found in macroeconomics.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Consider Okun's law, which relates GDP growth to the unemployment rate.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The unknown parameters $\beta _{0}$ and $\beta _{1}$ can be estimated.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] This means that if GDP growth increased by 1 percentage point, the unemployment rate would be predicted to drop by 1.77 * 1 points, other things held constant.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The model could then be tested for statistical significance as to whether an increase in GDP growth is associated with a decrease in unemployment, as hypothesized.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] If the estimate of $\beta _{1}$ were not significantly different from 0, the test would fail to find evidence that changes in the growth rate and unemployment rate were related.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The variance in a prediction of the dependent variable (unemployment) as a function of the independent variable (GDP growth) is given in polynomial least squares.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Econometric theory uses statistical theory and mathematical statistics to evaluate and develop econometric methods.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] An estimator is unbiased if its expected value is the true value of the parameter; it is consistent if it converges to the true value as the sample size gets larger, and it is efficient if the estimator has a lower standard error than other unbiased estimators for a given sample size.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Ordinary least squares (OLS) is often used for estimation since it provides the BLUE or "best linear unbiased estimator" (where "best" means most efficient, unbiased estimator) given the Gauss-Markov assumptions.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] When these assumptions are violated, or other statistical properties are desired, other estimation techniques such as maximum likelihood estimation, generalized method of moments, or generalized least squares are used.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Estimators that incorporate prior beliefs are advocated by those who favour Bayesian statistics over traditional, classical or "frequentist" approaches.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Econometrics uses standard statistical models to study economic questions, but most often these are based on observational data, rather than data from controlled experiments.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] In this, the design of observational studies in econometrics is similar to the design of studies in other observational disciplines, such as astronomy, epidemiology, sociology, and political science.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The study protocol guides analysis of data from an observational study, although exploratory data analysis may be useful for generating new hypotheses.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Economics often analyses systems of equations and inequalities, such as supply and demand hypothesized to be in equilibrium.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Consequently, the field of econometrics has developed methods for identification and estimation of simultaneous equations models.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] These methods are analogous to those used in other areas of science, such as system identification in systems analysis and control theory.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Such methods may allow researchers to estimate models and investigate their empirical consequences, without directly manipulating the system.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] In the absence of evidence from controlled experiments, econometricians often seek illuminating natural experiments or apply quasi-experimental methods to draw credible causal inference.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The methods include regression discontinuity design, instrumental variables, and difference-in-differences.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] This example assumes that the natural logarithm of a person's wage is a linear function of the number of years of education that person has acquired.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The parameter $\beta _{1}$ measures the increase in the natural log of the wage attributable to one more year of education.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The term $\varepsilon$ is a random variable representing all other factors that may have a direct influence on wage.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The econometric goal is to estimate the parameters, $\beta _{0}{\mbox{ and }}\beta _{1}$ under specific assumptions about the random variable $\varepsilon$ .
[src:econometrics/econometrics] For example, if $\varepsilon$ is uncorrelated with years of education, then the equation can be estimated with ordinary least squares.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] If the researcher could randomly assign people to different levels of education, the resulting data set would allow estimation of the effect of changes in years of education on wages.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] In reality, those experiments cannot be conducted.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Instead, the econometrician observes the years of education and the wages paid to people who differ along many dimensions.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Given this kind of data, the estimated coefficient on years of education in the equation above reflects both the effect of education on wages and the effect of other variables on wages, if those other variables were correlated with education.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] For example, people born in certain places may have higher wages and higher levels of education.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Unless the econometrician controls for place of birth in the above equation, the effect of birthplace on wages may be falsely attributed to the effect of education on wages.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The most obvious way to control for birthplace is to include a measure of its effect in the equation above.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Exclusion of birthplace, together with the assumption that $\epsilon$ is uncorrelated with education, produces a misspecified model.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Another technique is to include in the equation additional set of measured covariates which are not instrumental variables, yet render $\beta _{1}$ identifiable.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] An overview of econometric methods used to study this problem were provided by Card (1999).
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Integrating statistics into economic theory to make causal claims leads to disagreements within the discipline, prompting criticism of econometrics.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Most of these criticisms have been resolved as a result of the credibility revolution and the improved rigor of the potential outcomes framework, which is used today by applied economists, microeconomists, and econometricians to generate causal inferences.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] While econometricians began developing methods in the mid-1960s to improve statistical measures, the 2009 publication of *Mostly Harmless Econometrics* by economists Joshua D.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Angrist and Jörn-Steffen Pischke has summarized the advances in econometric modeling.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Structural causal modeling, which attempts to formalize the limitations of quasi-experimental methods from a causal perspective and enables experimenters to quantify the risks of quasi-experimental research precisely, is the primary academic response to this critique.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Like other forms of statistical analysis, badly specified econometric models may show a spurious relationship where two variables are correlated but causally unrelated.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] She also argues that some economists fail to use economic reasoning in model selection, especially when deciding which variables to include in a regression.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] In some cases, economic variables cannot be experimentally manipulated as treatments randomly assigned to subjects.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] In such cases, economists rely on observational studies, often using data sets with many strongly associated covariates, resulting in enormous numbers of models with similar explanatory ability but different covariates and regression estimates.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Regarding the plurality of models compatible with observational data-sets, Edward Leamer urged that "professionals ... properly withhold belief until an inference can be shown to be adequately insensitive to the choice of assumptions".
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Like other forms of statistical analysis, badly specified econometric models may show a spurious correlation where two variables are correlated but causally unrelated.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Economist Ronald Coase is widely reported to have said "if you torture the data long enough it will confess".
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Deirdre McCloskey argues that in published econometric work, economists often fail to use economic reasoning for including or excluding variables, equivocate statistical significance with substantial significance, and fail to report the *power* of their findings.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Economic variables are observed in reality, and therefore are not readily isolated for experimental testing.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Today, this critique is unbinding, as advances in identification are stronger.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Identification today may report the average treatment effect (ATE), the average treatment effect *on the treated* (ATT), or the *local* average treatment effect (LATE).
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Specification bias, or *selection bias* can be easily removed, through advances in sampling techniques and the ability to sample much larger populations through improved communications, data storage, and randomization techniques.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Secondly, collinearity can be easily controlled for using instrumental variables.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] By reporting either ATT or LATE, we can control for or eliminate heterogeneous error, reporting only the effects within the defined group.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Economists, when using data, may have many explanatory variables they want to use that are highly collinear, such that researcher bias may be important in variable selection.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] P-hacking is not accepted in economics, and the requirement to disclose original data and the code to perform statistical analysis.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] However Sala-I-Martin argued, it's possible to specify two models suggesting contrary relation between two variables.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The phenomenon was labeled *emerging recalcitrant result* phenomenon by Robert Goldfarb.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] This is known as two-way causality, and should be discussed with respect to the underlying theory that the mechanism is attempting to capture.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Kennedy (1998, p 1-2) reports econometricians as being accused of *using sledgehammers to crack open peanuts*.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] That is they use a wide range of complex statistical techniques *while turning a blind eye to data deficiencies and the many questionable assumptions required for the application of these techniques*.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] He looks at two well-cited macroeconometric studies (Hansen & Singleton (1982, 1983), and Bernanke (1986)), and argues that while both make brilliant use of econometric methods, neither paper speaks to formal theoretical proof.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Robert Lucas criticised the use of overly simplistic econometric models of the macroeconomy to predict the implications of economic policy, arguing that the structural relationships observed in historical models break down when decision-makers adjust their preferences in response to policy changes.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Lucas argued that policy conclusions drawn from contemporary large-scale macroeconometric models were invalid, as economic actors would revise their expectations about the future and adjust their behaviour accordingly.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The current-day Austrian School of Economics typically rejects much of econometric modeling.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The historical data used to make econometric models, they claim, represent behavior under circumstances idiosyncratic to the past; thus, econometric models show correlational rather than causal relationships.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Econometricians have addressed this criticism by adopting quasi-experimental methodologies.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Austrian school economists remain skeptical of these corrected models, maintaining their belief that statistical methods are unsuited to the social sciences.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The Austrian School holds that the counterfactual must be known for a causal relationship to be established.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The counterfactual changes could then be extracted from the observed changes, leaving only the changes attributable to the variable.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Meeting this critique is very challenging since "there is no dependable method for ascertaining the uniquely correct counterfactual" for historical data.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] For non-historical data, the Austrian critique is met with randomized controlled trials.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] Randomized controlled trials must be purposefully prepared, which historical data is not.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] The use of randomized controlled trials is becoming more common in social science research.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] If the data is not from a randomized controlled trial, econometricians meet the Austrian critique with quasi-experimental methodologies, including identifying and exploiting natural experiments.
[src:econometrics/econometrics] These methodologies attempt to extract the counterfactual post hoc, thereby justifying the use of parametric statistical tools.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] In econometrics, **endogeneity** broadly refers to situations in which an explanatory variable is correlated with the error term.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] In simplest terms, **endogeneity** means that a factor or cause one uses to explain something as an outcome is also being influenced by that same thing.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] For example, education can affect income, but income can also affect how much education someone gets.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] When this happens, one's analysis might wrongly estimate cause and effect.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] The thing one thinks is causing change is also being influenced by the outcome, making the results unreliable.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] The concept originates from simultaneous equations models, in which one distinguishes variables whose values are determined within the economic model (endogenous) from those that are predetermined (exogenous).
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Ignoring simultaneity in estimation leads to biased and inconsistent estimators, as it violates the exogeneity condition of the Gauss–Markov theorem.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] This issue is often overlooked in non-experimental research, which limits the validity of causal inference and the ability to draw reliable policy recommendations.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Common solutions to address endogeneity include the use of instrumental variable techniques, which provide consistent estimators by introducing variables that are correlated with the endogenous explanatory variable but uncorrelated with the error term.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Besides simultaneity, correlation between explanatory variables and the error term can arise when an unobserved or omitted variable is confounding both independent and dependent variables, or when independent variables are measured with error.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] In a stochastic model, the notion of the *usual exogeneity*, *sequential exogeneity*, *strong/strict exogeneity* can be defined.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] **Exogeneity** is articulated in such a way that a variable or variables is exogenous for parameter $\alpha$ .
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Even if a variable is exogenous for parameter $\alpha$ , it might be endogenous for parameter $\beta$ .
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] When the explanatory variables are not stochastic, then they are strong exogenous for all the parameters.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] If the independent variable is correlated with the error term in a regression model then the estimate of the regression coefficient in an ordinary least squares (OLS) regression is biased; however if the correlation is not contemporaneous, then the coefficient estimate may still be consistent.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] There are many methods of correcting the bias, including instrumental variable regression and Heckman selection correction.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] The following are some common sources of endogeneity.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] In this case, the endogeneity comes from an uncontrolled confounding variable, a variable that is correlated with both the independent variable in the model and with the error term.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] but $z_{i}$ is omitted from the regression model (perhaps because there is no way to measure it directly).
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] where $\varepsilon _{i}=\gamma z_{i}+u_{i}$ (thus, the $z_{i}$ term has been absorbed into the error term).
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] If the correlation of x and z is not 0 and z separately affects y (meaning $\gamma \neq 0$ ), then x is correlated with the error term $\varepsilon$ .
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Here, x is not exogenous for $\alpha$ and $\beta$ , since, given x , the distribution of y depends not only on $\alpha$ and $\beta$ , but also on z and $\gamma$ .
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Suppose that a perfect measure of an independent variable is impossible.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] That is, instead of observing $x_{i}^{*}$ , what is actually observed is $x_{i}=x_{i}^{*}+\nu _{i}$ where $\nu _{i}$ is the measurement error or "noise".
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Since both $x_{i}$ and $u_{i}$ depend on $\nu _{i}$ , they are correlated, so the OLS estimation of $\beta$ will be biased downward.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Measurement error in the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ , does not cause endogeneity, though it does increase the variance of the error term.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Estimating either equation by itself results in endogeneity.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] In the case of the first structural equation, $E(z_{i}u_{i})\neq 0$ .
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Therefore, attempts at estimating either structural equation will be hampered by endogeneity.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] The endogeneity problem is particularly relevant in the context of time series analysis of causal processes.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] It is common for some factors within a causal system to be dependent for their value in period *t* on the values of other factors in the causal system in period *t* − 1.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Suppose that the level of pest infestation is independent of all other factors within a given period, but is influenced by the level of rainfall and fertilizer in the preceding period.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] In this instance it would be correct to say that infestation is exogenous within the period, but endogenous over time.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] If the variable *x* is sequential exogenous for parameter $\alpha$ , and *y* does not cause *x* in the Granger sense, then the variable *x* is strongly/strictly exogenous for the parameter $\alpha$ .
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] The concept was formalized by Jean-François Richard (1980) and further analyzed by Robert F.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Hendry, and Richard (1983) in Econometrica.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] This condition allows for the errors to be correlated with future realizations of the regressors, accommodating feedback mechanisms where an outcome variable in one period influences regressor values in future periods.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Equivalently, weak exogeneity requires regressors and lagged response variables to be **predetermined**—that is, determined prior to the current period.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] A common example of a weakly exogenous variable is consumption in models with credit constraints and rational expectations.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] Here, consumption is predetermined but not strictly exogenous.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] An unpredictable negative income shock will be uncorrelated with past (and potentially current) consumption, but will surely be correlated with future consumption—the individual will be forced to adjust their future consumption to accommodate their poorer state, inducing correlation.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] If the shock affects current consumption, predeterminedness (defined now as lags only) provides potential instruments—lagged values of the variable.
[src:econometrics/endogeneity-econometrics] The presence of predetermined variables is a motivating factor in the Arellano–Bond estimator.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The errors do not need to be normal, nor do they need to be independent and identically distributed (only uncorrelated with mean zero and homoscedastic with finite variance).
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The requirement that the estimator be unbiased cannot be dropped, since biased estimators exist with lower variance.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] See, for example, the James–Stein estimator (which also drops linearity), ridge regression, or simply any degenerate estimator.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The theorem was named after Carl Friedrich Gauss and Andrey Markov, although Gauss' work significantly predates Markov's.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] But while Gauss derived the result under the assumption of independence and normality, Markov reduced the assumptions to the form stated above.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] A further generalization to non-spherical errors was given by Alexander Aitken.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Suppose we are given two random variables $X,Y$ and that we want to find the best linear estimator of Y given X , using the best linear estimator ${\hat {Y}}=\alpha X+\mu ,$ where the parameters $\alpha$ and $\mu$ are both real numbers.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Such an estimator ${\hat {Y}}$ would have the same mean and standard deviation as Y , that is, $\mu _{\hat {Y}}=\mu _{Y},\sigma _{\hat {Y}}=\sigma _{Y}$ .
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Therefore, if the vector X has respective mean and standard deviation $\mu _{x},\sigma _{x}$ , the best linear estimator would be ${\hat {Y}}=\sigma _{y}{\frac {(X-\mu _{x})}{\sigma _{x}}}+\mu _{y},$ since ${\hat {Y}}$ has the same mean and standard deviation as Y .
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The random variables $\varepsilon _{i}$ are called the "disturbance", "noise" or simply "error" (will be contrasted with "residual" later in the article; see errors and residuals in statistics).
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Note that to include a constant in the model above, one can choose to introduce the constant as a variable $\beta _{K+1}$ with a newly introduced last column of X being unity i.e., $X_{i(K+1)}=1$ for all i .
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Now, let ${\textstyle \sum _{j=1}^{K}\lambda _{j}\beta _{j}}$ be some linear combination of the coefficients.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] This is equivalent to the condition that $\operatorname {Var} ({\tilde {\beta }})-\operatorname {Var} ({\hat {\beta }})$ is a positive semi-definite matrix for every other linear unbiased estimator ${\widetilde {\beta }}$ .
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The theorem now states that the OLS estimator is a best linear unbiased estimator (BLUE).
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The main idea of the proof is that the least-squares estimator is uncorrelated with every linear unbiased estimator of zero, i.e., with every linear combination $a_{1}y_{1}+\cdots +a_{n}y_{n}$ whose coefficients do not depend upon the unobservable $\beta$ but whose expected value is always zero.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Proof that the OLS indeed *minimizes* the sum of squares of residuals may proceed as follows with a calculation of the Hessian matrix and showing that it is positive definite.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Finally, as eigenvector $\mathbf {k}$ was arbitrary, it means all eigenvalues of ${\mathcal {H}}$ are positive, therefore ${\mathcal {H}}$ is positive definite.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Thus, ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}=\left(X^{\operatorname {T} }X\right)^{-1}X^{\operatorname {T} }Y$ is indeed a global minimum.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Or, just see that for all vectors $\mathbf {v} ,\mathbf {v} ^{\operatorname {T} }X^{\operatorname {T} }X\mathbf {v} =\|\mathbf {X} \mathbf {v} \|^{2}\geq 0$ .
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] So the Hessian is positive definite if full rank.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Let ${\tilde {\beta }}=Cy$ be another linear estimator of $\beta$ with $C=(X^{\operatorname {T} }X)^{-1}X^{\operatorname {T} }+D$ where D is a $K\times n$ non-zero matrix.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] As we're restricting to *unbiased* estimators, minimum mean squared error implies minimum variance.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The goal is therefore to show that such an estimator has a variance no smaller than that of ${\widehat {\beta }},$ the OLS estimator.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Therefore, since $\beta$ is **un**observable, ${\tilde {\beta }}$ is unbiased if and only if $DX=0$ .
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Since $DD^{\operatorname {T} }$ is a positive semidefinite matrix, $\operatorname {Var} \left({\tilde {\beta }}\right)$ exceeds $\operatorname {Var} \left({\widehat {\beta }}\right)$ by a positive semidefinite matrix.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] To see this, let $\ell ^{\operatorname {T} }{\tilde {\beta }}$ another linear unbiased estimator of $\ell ^{\operatorname {T} }\beta$ .
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Moreover, equality holds if and only if $D^{\operatorname {T} }\ell =0$ .
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] This proves that the equality holds if and only if $\ell ^{\operatorname {T} }{\tilde {\beta }}=\ell ^{\operatorname {T} }{\widehat {\beta }}$ which gives the uniqueness of the OLS estimator as a BLUE.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The generalized least squares (GLS), developed by Aitken, extends the Gauss–Markov theorem to the case where the error vector has a non-scalar covariance matrix.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] In most treatments of OLS, the regressors (parameters of interest) in the design matrix $\mathbf {X}$ are assumed to be fixed in repeated samples.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] This assumption is considered inappropriate for a predominantly nonexperimental science like econometrics.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Instead, the assumptions of the Gauss–Markov theorem are stated conditional on $\mathbf {X}$ .
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The dependent variable is assumed to be a linear function of the variables specified in the model.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The specification must be linear in its parameters.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] This does not mean that there must be a linear relationship between the independent and dependent variables.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The independent variables can take non-linear forms as long as the parameters are linear.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The equation $y=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}x^{2},$ qualifies as linear while $y=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}^{2}x$ can be transformed to be linear by replacing $\beta _{1}^{2}$ by another parameter, say $\gamma$ .
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] An equation with a parameter dependent on an independent variable does not qualify as linear, for example $y=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}(x)\cdot x$ , where $\beta _{1}(x)$ is a function of x .
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Data transformations are often used to convert an equation into a linear form.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] This assumption also covers specification issues: assuming that the proper functional form has been selected and there are no omitted variables.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] One should be aware, however, that the parameters that minimize the residuals of the transformed equation do not necessarily minimize the residuals of the original equation.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Geometrically, this assumption implies that $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ and $\varepsilon _{i}$ are orthogonal to each other, so that their inner product (i.e., their cross moment) is zero.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] This assumption is violated if the explanatory variables are measured with error, or are endogenous.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Endogeneity can be the result of simultaneity, where causality flows back and forth between both the dependent and independent variable.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Instrumental variable techniques are commonly used to address this problem.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The sample data matrix $\mathbf {X}$ must have full column rank.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Otherwise $\mathbf {X} ^{\operatorname {T} }\mathbf {X}$ is not invertible and the OLS estimator cannot be computed.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] A violation of this assumption is perfect multicollinearity, i.e. some explanatory variables are linearly dependent.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] One scenario in which this will occur is called "dummy variable trap," when a base dummy variable is not omitted resulting in perfect correlation between the dummy variables and the constant term.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Multicollinearity (as long as it is not "perfect") can be present resulting in a less efficient, but still unbiased estimate.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The estimates will be less precise and highly sensitive to particular sets of data.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Multicollinearity can be detected from condition number or the variance inflation factor, among other tests.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] The outer product of the error vector must be spherical.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] This implies the error term has uniform variance (homoscedasticity) and no serial correlation.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] If this assumption is violated, OLS is still unbiased, but inefficient.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Heteroskedasticity occurs when the amount of error is correlated with an independent variable.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] For example, in a regression on food expenditure and income, the error is correlated with income.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Low income people generally spend a similar amount on food, while high income people may spend a very large amount or as little as low income people spend.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Heteroskedastic can also be caused by changes in measurement practices.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] For example, as statistical offices improve their data, measurement error decreases, so the error term declines over time.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] This assumption is violated when there is autocorrelation.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Autocorrelation can be visualized on a data plot when a given observation is more likely to lie above a fitted line if adjacent observations also lie above the fitted regression line.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Autocorrelation is common in time series data where a data series may experience "inertia." If a dependent variable takes a while to fully absorb a shock.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Spatial autocorrelation can also occur geographic areas are likely to have similar errors.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] Autocorrelation may be the result of misspecification such as choosing the wrong functional form.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] In these cases, correcting the specification is one possible way to deal with autocorrelation.
[src:econometrics/gauss-markov-theorem] When the spherical errors assumption may be violated, the generalized least squares estimator can be shown to be BLUE.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] In statistics, a sequence of random variables is **homoscedastic** (/ˌhoʊmoʊskəˈdæstɪk/) if all its random variables have the same finite variance; this is also known as **homogeneity of variance**.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The complementary notion is called **heteroscedasticity**, also known as **heterogeneity of variance**.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The term originates from the Ancient Greek σκεδάννυμι *skedánnymi*, 'to scatter'.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Assuming a variable is homoscedastic when in reality it is heteroscedastic (/ˌhɛtəroʊskəˈdæstɪk/) results in unbiased but inefficient point estimates and in biased estimates of standard errors, and may result in overestimating the goodness of fit as measured by the Pearson coefficient.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The existence of heteroscedasticity is a major concern in regression analysis and the analysis of variance, as it invalidates statistical tests of significance which assume that the modelling errors all have the same variance.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] While the ordinary least squares (OLS) estimator is still unbiased in the presence of heteroscedasticity, it is inefficient and inference based on the assumption of homoskedasticity is misleading.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] In that case, generalized least squares (GLS) was frequently used in the past.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Nowadays, standard practice in econometrics is to include heteroskedasticity-consistent standard errors instead of using GLS, as GLS can exhibit strong bias in small samples if the actual skedastic function is unknown.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Because heteroscedasticity concerns expectations of the second moment of the errors, its presence is referred to as misspecification of the second order.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The econometrician Robert Engle was awarded the 2003 Nobel Memorial Prize for Economics for his studies on regression analysis in the presence of heteroscedasticity, which led to his formulation of the autoregressive conditional heteroscedasticity (ARCH) modeling technique.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Consider the linear regression equation $y_{i}=x_{i}\beta _{i}+\varepsilon _{i},\ i=1,\ldots ,N,$ where the dependent random variable $y_{i}$ equals the deterministic variable $x_{i}$ times coefficient $\beta _{i}$ plus a random disturbance term $\varepsilon _{i}$ that has mean zero.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The disturbances are homoscedastic if the variance of $\varepsilon _{i}$ is a constant $\sigma ^{2}$ ; otherwise, they are heteroscedastic.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] In particular, the disturbances are heteroscedastic if the variance of $\varepsilon _{i}$ depends on i or on the value of $x_{i}$ .
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] One way they might be heteroscedastic is if $\sigma _{i}^{2}=x_{i}\sigma ^{2}$ (an example of a scedastic function), so the variance is proportional to the value of x .
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] More generally, if the variance-covariance matrix of disturbance $\varepsilon _{i}$ across i has a nonconstant diagonal, the disturbance is heteroscedastic.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The matrices below are covariances when there are just three observations across time.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The disturbance in matrix A is homoscedastic; this is the simple case where OLS is the best linear unbiased estimator.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The disturbances in matrices B and C are heteroscedastic.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] In matrix B, the variance is time-varying, increasing steadily across time; in matrix C, the variance depends on the value of x .
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The disturbance in matrix D is homoscedastic because the diagonal variances are constant, even though the off-diagonal covariances are non-zero and ordinary least squares is inefficient for a different reason: serial correlation.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Heteroscedasticity often occurs when there is a large difference among the sizes of the observations.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] A classic example of heteroscedasticity is that of income versus expenditure on meals.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] A wealthy person may eat inexpensive food sometimes and expensive food at other times.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] A poor person will almost always eat inexpensive food.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Therefore, people with higher incomes exhibit greater variability in expenditures on food.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] At a rocket launch, an observer measures the distance traveled by the rocket once per second.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] In the first couple of seconds, the measurements may be accurate to the nearest centimeter.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] After five minutes, the accuracy of the measurements may be good only to 100 m, because of the increased distance, atmospheric distortion, and a variety of other factors.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] So the measurements of distance may exhibit heteroscedasticity.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] One of the assumptions of the classical linear regression model is that there is no heteroscedasticity.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Breaking this assumption means that the Gauss–Markov theorem does not apply, meaning that OLS estimators are not the Best Linear Unbiased Estimators (BLUE) and their variance is not the lowest of all other unbiased estimators.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Heteroscedasticity does *not* cause ordinary least squares coefficient estimates to be biased, although it can cause ordinary least squares estimates of the variance (and, thus, standard errors) of the coefficients to be biased, possibly above or below the true of population variance.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Thus, regression analysis using heteroscedastic data will still provide an unbiased estimate for the relationship between the predictor variable and the outcome, but standard errors and therefore inferences obtained from data analysis are suspect.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Biased standard errors lead to biased inference, so results of hypothesis tests are possibly wrong.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] For example, if OLS is performed on a heteroscedastic data set, yielding biased standard error estimation, a researcher might fail to reject a null hypothesis at a given significance level, when that null hypothesis was actually uncharacteristic of the actual population (making a type II error).
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Under certain assumptions, the OLS estimator has a normal asymptotic distribution when properly normalized and centered (even when the data does not come from a normal distribution).
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] This result is used to justify using a normal distribution, or a chi square distribution (depending on how the test statistic is calculated), when conducting a hypothesis test.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] This holds even under heteroscedasticity.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] More precisely, the OLS estimator in the presence of heteroscedasticity is asymptotically normal, when properly normalized and centered, with a variance-covariance matrix that differs from the case of homoscedasticity.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] In 1980, White proposed a consistent estimator for the variance-covariance matrix of the asymptotic distribution of the OLS estimator.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] This validates the use of hypothesis testing using OLS estimators and White's variance-covariance estimator under heteroscedasticity.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Heteroscedasticity is also a major practical issue encountered in ANOVA problems.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The F test can still be used in some circumstances.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] However, it has been said that students in econometrics should not overreact to heteroscedasticity.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Yet, in the context of binary choice models (Logit or Probit), heteroscedasticity will only result in a positive scaling effect on the asymptotic mean of the misspecified MLE (i.e. the model that ignores heteroscedasticity).
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] As a result, the predictions which are based on the misspecified MLE will remain correct.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] In addition, the misspecified Probit and Logit MLE will be asymptotically normally distributed which allows performing the usual significance tests (with the appropriate variance-covariance matrix).
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] However, regarding the general hypothesis testing, as pointed out by Greene, "simply computing a robust covariance matrix for an otherwise inconsistent estimator does not give it redemption.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] There are several common corrections for heteroscedasticity.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Residuals can be tested for homoscedasticity using the Breusch–Pagan test, which performs an auxiliary regression of the squared residuals on the independent variables.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] From this auxiliary regression, the explained sum of squares is retained, divided by two, and then becomes the test statistic for a chi-squared distribution with the degrees of freedom equal to the number of independent variables.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The null hypothesis of this chi-squared test is homoscedasticity, and the alternative hypothesis would indicate heteroscedasticity.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Since the Breusch–Pagan test is sensitive to departures from normality or small sample sizes, the Koenker–Bassett or 'generalized Breusch–Pagan' test is commonly used instead.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] From the auxiliary regression, it retains the R-squared value which is then multiplied by the sample size, and then becomes the test statistic for a chi-squared distribution (and uses the same degrees of freedom).
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Although it is not necessary for the Koenker–Bassett test, the Breusch–Pagan test requires that the squared residuals also be divided by the residual sum of squares divided by the sample size.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Testing for groupwise heteroscedasticity can be done with the Goldfeld–Quandt test.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Due to the standard use of heteroskedasticity-consistent Standard Errors and the problem of Pre-test, econometricians nowadays rarely use tests for conditional heteroskedasticity.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Although tests for heteroscedasticity between groups can formally be considered as a special case of testing within regression models, some tests have structures specific to this case.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Two or more normal distributions, $N(\mu _{1},\Sigma _{1}),N(\mu _{2},\Sigma _{2}),$ are both homoscedastic and lack serial correlation if they share the same diagonals in their covariance matrix, $\Sigma _{1}{ii}=\Sigma _{2}{jj},\ \forall i=j.$ and their non-diagonal entries are zero.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Homoscedastic distributions are especially useful to derive statistical pattern recognition and machine learning algorithms.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] One popular example of an algorithm that assumes homoscedasticity is Fisher's linear discriminant analysis.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The concept of homoscedasticity can be applied to distributions on spheres.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] The study of homescedasticity and heteroscedasticity has been generalized to the multivariate case, which deals with the covariances of vector observations instead of the variance of scalar observations.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] One version of this is to use covariance matrices as the multivariate measure of dispersion.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Several authors have considered tests in this context, for both regression and grouped-data situations.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Bartlett's test for heteroscedasticity between grouped data, used most commonly in the univariate case, has also been extended for the multivariate case, but a tractable solution only exists for 2 groups.
[src:econometrics/heteroscedasticity] Approximations exist for more than two groups, and they are both called Box's M test.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Intuitively, IVs are used when an explanatory (also known as independent or predictor) variable of interest is correlated with the error term (endogenous), in which case ordinary least squares and ANOVA give biased results.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Instrumental variable methods allow for consistent estimation when the explanatory variables (covariates) are correlated with the error terms in a regression model.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] 3. the covariates are subject to measurement error.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Explanatory variables that suffer from one or more of these issues in the context of a regression are sometimes referred to as endogenous.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In this situation, ordinary least squares produces biased and inconsistent estimates.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] However, if an *instrument* is available, consistent estimates may still be obtained.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] An instrument is a variable that does not itself belong in the explanatory equation but is correlated with the endogenous explanatory variables, conditionally on the value of other covariates.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Informally, in attempting to estimate the causal effect of some variable *X* ("covariate" or "explanatory variable") on another *Y* ("dependent variable"), an *instrument* is a third variable *Z* which affects *Y* only through its effect on *X*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] For example, suppose a researcher wishes to estimate the causal effect of smoking (*X*) on general health (*Y*).
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Correlation between smoking and health does not imply that smoking causes poor health because other variables, such as depression, may affect both health and smoking, or because health may affect smoking.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] It is not possible to conduct controlled experiments on smoking status in the general population.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The researcher may attempt to estimate the causal effect of smoking on health from observational data by using the tax rate for tobacco products (*Z*) as an instrument for smoking.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The tax rate for tobacco products is a reasonable choice for an instrument because the researcher assumes that it can only be correlated with health through its effect on smoking.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] If the researcher then finds tobacco taxes and state of health to be correlated, this may be viewed as evidence that smoking causes changes in health.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The first use of an instrument variable occurred in a 1928 book by Philip G.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Wright, best known for his excellent description of the production, transport and sale of vegetable and animal oils in the early 1900s in the United States.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In 1945, Olav Reiersøl applied the same approach in the context of errors-in-variables models in his dissertation, giving the method its name.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Wright attempted to determine the supply and demand for butter using panel data on prices and quantities sold in the United States.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The idea was that a regression analysis could produce a demand or supply curve because they are formed by the path between prices and quantities demanded or supplied.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The problem was that the observational data did not form a demand or supply curve as such, but rather a cloud of point observations that took different shapes under varying market conditions.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] It seemed that making deductions from the data remained elusive.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The problem was that price affected both supply and demand so that a function describing only one of the two could not be constructed directly from the observational data.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Wright correctly concluded that he needed a variable that correlated with either demand or supply but not both – that is, an instrumental variable.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] After much deliberation, Wright decided to use regional rainfall as his instrumental variable: he concluded that rainfall affected grass production and hence milk production and ultimately butter supply, but not butter demand.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In this way he was able to construct a regression equation with only the instrumental variable of price and supply.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Formal definitions of instrumental variables, using counterfactuals and graphical criteria, were given by Judea Pearl in 2000.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Angrist and Krueger (2001) present a survey of the history and uses of instrumental variable techniques.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Notions of causality in econometrics, and their relationship with instrumental variables and other methods, are discussed by Heckman (2008).
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] While the ideas behind IV extend to a broad class of models, a very common context for IV is in linear regression.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] X is a matrix, usually with a column of ones and perhaps with additional columns for other covariates.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Consider how an instrument allows $\beta$ to be recovered.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Recall that OLS solves for ${\widehat {\beta }}$ such that $\operatorname {cov} (X,{\widehat {U}})=0$ (when we minimize the sum of squared errors, $\min _{\beta }(Y-X\beta )'(Y-X\beta )$ , the first-order condition is exactly $X'(Y-X{\widehat {\beta }})=X'{\widehat {U}}=0$ ).
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] If the true model is believed to have $\operatorname {cov} (X,U)\neq 0$ due to any of the reasons listed above—for example, if there is an omitted variable which affects both X and Y separately—then this OLS procedure will *not* yield the causal impact of X on Y .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] OLS will simply pick the parameter that makes the resulting errors appear uncorrelated with X .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Consider for simplicity the single-variable case.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In this case, the coefficient on the regressor of interest is given by ${\widehat {\beta }}={\frac {\operatorname {cov} (x,y)}{\operatorname {var} (x)}}$ .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] where $\beta ^{*}$ is what the estimated coefficient vector would be if $\operatorname {cov} (x,u)=0$ .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In this case, it can be shown that $\beta ^{*}$ is an unbiased estimator of $\beta$ .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] If $\operatorname {cov} (x,u)\neq 0$ in the underlying model that we believe, then OLS gives an inconsistent estimate which does *not* reflect the underlying causal effect of interest.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] IV helps to fix this problem by identifying the parameters ${\beta }$ not based on whether x is uncorrelated with u , but based on whether another variable z is uncorrelated with u .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] If theory suggests that z is related to x (the first stage) but uncorrelated with u (the exclusion restriction), then IV may identify the causal parameter of interest where OLS fails.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Because there are multiple specific ways of using and deriving IV estimators even in just the linear case (IV, 2SLS, GMM), we save further discussion for the Estimation section below.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] IV techniques have been developed among a much broader class of non-linear models.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] General definitions of instrumental variables, using counterfactual and graphical formalism, were given by Pearl (2000; p.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] where $\perp \!\!\!\perp$ stands for *d*-separation and $G_{\overline {X}}$ stands for the graph in which all arrows entering *X* are cut off.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] where *Y**x* stands for the value that *Y* would attain had *X* been *x* and $\perp \!\!\!\perp$ stands for independence.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] If there are additional covariates *W* then the above definitions are modified so that *Z* qualifies as an instrument if the given criteria hold conditional on *W*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The error term *U* stands for all exogenous factors that affect *Y* when *X* is held constant.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The instrument *Z* should be independent of *U*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The instrument *Z* should not affect *Y* when *X* is held constant (exclusion restriction).
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The instrument *Z* should not be independent of *X*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] These conditions do not rely on specific functional form of the equations and are applicable therefore to nonlinear equations, where *U* can be non-additive (see Non-parametric analysis).
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] They are also applicable to a system of multiple equations, in which *X* (and other factors) affect *Y* through several intermediate variables.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] An instrumental variable need not be a cause of *X*; a proxy of such cause may also be used, if it satisfies conditions 1–5.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The exclusion restriction (condition 4) is redundant; it follows from conditions 2 and 3.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Since *U* is unobserved, the requirement that *Z* be independent of *U* cannot be inferred from data and must instead be determined from the model structure, i.e., the data-generating process.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Causal graphs are a representation of this structure, and the graphical definition given above can be used to quickly determine whether a variable *Z* qualifies as an instrumental variable given a set of covariates *W*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] To see how, consider the following example.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Suppose that we wish to estimate the effect of a university tutoring program on grade point average (GPA).
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The relationship between attending the tutoring program and GPA may be confounded by a number of factors.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Students who attend the tutoring program may care more about their grades or may be struggling with their work.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] This confounding is depicted in the Figures 1–3 on the right through the bidirected arc between Tutoring Program and GPA.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] If students are assigned to dormitories at random, the proximity of the student's dorm to the tutoring program is a natural candidate for being an instrumental variable.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] However, what if the tutoring program is located in the college library?
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In that case, Proximity may also cause students to spend more time at the library, which in turn improves their GPA (see Figure 1).
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Using the causal graph depicted in the Figure 2, we see that Proximity does not qualify as an instrumental variable because it is connected to GPA through the path Proximity $\rightarrow$ Library Hours $\rightarrow$ GPA in $G_{\overline {X}}$ .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] However, if we control for Library Hours by adding it as a covariate then Proximity becomes an instrumental variable, since Proximity is separated from GPA given Library Hours in $G_{\overline {X}}$ .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Now, suppose that we notice that a student's "natural ability" affects his or her number of hours in the library as well as his or her GPA, as in Figure 3.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Using the causal graph, we see that Library Hours is a collider and conditioning on it opens the path Proximity $\rightarrow$ Library Hours $\leftrightarrow$ GPA.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] As a result, Proximity cannot be used as an instrumental variable.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Finally, suppose that Library Hours does not actually affect GPA because students who do not study in the library simply study elsewhere, as in Figure 4.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In this case, controlling for Library Hours still opens a spurious path from Proximity to GPA.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] However, if we do not control for Library Hours and remove it as a covariate then Proximity can again be used an instrumental variable.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] We now revisit and expand upon the mechanics of IV in greater detail.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The parameter vector $\beta$ is the causal effect on $y_{i}$ of a one unit change in each element of $X_{i}$ , holding all other causes of $y_{i}$ constant.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The econometric goal is to estimate $\beta$ .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] For simplicity's sake assume the draws of *e* are uncorrelated and that they are drawn from distributions with the same variance (that is, that the errors are serially uncorrelated and homoskedastic).
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Suppose also that a regression model of nominally the same form is proposed.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] where *X*, *y* and *e* denote column vectors of length *T*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] This equation is similar to the equation involving $\operatorname {cov} (X,y)$ in the introduction (this is the matrix version of that equation).
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] When *X* and *e* are uncorrelated, under certain regularity conditions the second term has an expected value conditional on *X* of zero and converges to zero in the limit, so the estimator is unbiased and consistent.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] When *X* and the other unmeasured, causal variables collapsed into the *e* term are correlated, however, the OLS estimator is generally biased and inconsistent for *β*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In this case, it is valid to use the estimates to predict values of *y* given values of *X*, but the estimate does not recover the causal effect of *X* on *y*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] To recover the underlying parameter $\beta$ , we introduce a set of variables *Z* that is highly correlated with each endogenous component of *X* but (in our underlying model) is not correlated with *e*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] For simplicity, one might consider *X* to be a *T* × 2 matrix composed of a column of constants and one endogenous variable, and *Z* to be a *T* × 2 consisting of a column of constants and one instrumental variable.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] However, this technique generalizes to *X* being a matrix of a constant and, say, 5 endogenous variables, with *Z* being a matrix composed of a constant and 5 instruments.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In the discussion that follows, we will assume that *X* is a *T* × *K* matrix and leave this value *K* unspecified.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] An estimator in which *X* and *Z* are both *T* × *K* matrices is referred to as just-identified .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] As long as $Z^{\mathrm {T} }e=0$ in the underlying process which generates the data, the appropriate use of the IV estimator will identify this parameter.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] This works because IV solves for the unique parameter that satisfies $Z^{\mathrm {T} }e=0$ , and therefore hones in on the true underlying parameter as the sample size grows.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Now an extension: suppose that there are more instruments than there are covariates in the equation of interest, so that *Z* is a *T × M* matrix with *M > K*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] This is often called the **over-identified** case.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In this case, the generalized method of moments (GMM) can be used.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] This expression collapses to the first when the number of instruments is equal to the number of covariates in the equation of interest.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The over-identified IV is therefore a generalization of the just-identified IV.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In the just-identified case, we have as many instruments as covariates, so that the dimension of *X* is the same as that of *Z*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Hence, $X^{\mathrm {T} }Z,Z^{\mathrm {T} }Z$ and $Z^{\mathrm {T} }X$ are all squared matrices of the same dimension.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] There is an equivalent under-identified estimator for the case where *m < k*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Since the parameters are the solutions to a set of linear equations, an under-identified model using the set of equations $Z'v=0$ does not have a unique solution.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] One computational method which can be used to calculate IV estimates is two-stage least squares (2SLS or TSLS).
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In the first stage, each explanatory variable that is an endogenous covariate in the equation of interest is regressed on all of the exogenous variables in the model, including both exogenous covariates in the equation of interest and the excluded instruments.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] This method is only valid in linear models.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] For categorical endogenous covariates, one might be tempted to use a different first stage than ordinary least squares, such as a probit model for the first stage followed by OLS for the second.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] This is commonly known in the econometric literature as the *forbidden regression*, because second-stage IV parameter estimates are consistent only in special cases.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The resulting estimator of $\beta$ is numerically identical to the expression displayed above.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] A small correction must be made to the sum-of-squared residuals in the second-stage fitted model in order that the covariance matrix of $\beta$ is calculated correctly.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] where f and g are two arbitrary functions and Z is independent of U .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Balke and Pearl [1997] derived tight bounds on ACE and showed that these can provide valuable information on the sign and size of ACE.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In linear analysis, there is no test to falsify the assumption the Z is instrumental relative to the pair $(X,Y)$ .
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] This is not the case when X is discrete.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The exposition above assumes that the causal effect of interest does not vary across observations, that is, that $\beta$ is a constant.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Generally, different subjects will respond in different ways to changes in the "treatment" *x*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] When this possibility is recognized, the average effect in the population of a change in *x* on *y* may differ from the effect in a given subpopulation.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] For example, the average effect of a job training program may substantially differ across the group of people who actually receive the training and the group which chooses not to receive training.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] For these reasons, IV methods invoke implicit assumptions on behavioral response, or more generally assumptions over the correlation between the response to treatment and propensity to receive treatment.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The standard IV estimator can recover local average treatment effects (LATE) rather than average treatment effects (ATE).
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Imbens and Angrist (1994) demonstrate that the linear IV estimate can be interpreted under weak conditions as a weighted average of local average treatment effects, where the weights depend on the elasticity of the endogenous regressor to changes in the instrumental variables.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Roughly, that means that the effect of a variable is only revealed for the subpopulations affected by the observed changes in the instruments, and that subpopulations which respond most to changes in the instruments will have the largest effects on the magnitude of the IV estimate.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] This empirical approach does not, without further assumptions, tell the researcher anything about the effect of college among people who would either always or never get a college degree regardless of whether a local college exists.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] As Bound, Jaeger, and Baker (1995) note, a problem is caused by the selection of "weak" instruments, instruments that are poor predictors of the endogenous question predictor in the first-stage equation.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In this case, the prediction of the question predictor by the instrument will be poor and the predicted values will have very little variation.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Consequently, they are unlikely to have much success in predicting the ultimate outcome when they are used to replace the question predictor in the second-stage equation.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In the context of the smoking and health example discussed above, tobacco taxes are weak instruments for smoking if smoking status is largely unresponsive to changes in taxes.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] If higher taxes do not induce people to quit smoking (or not start smoking), then variation in tax rates tells us nothing about the effect of smoking on health.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] If taxes affect health through channels other than through their effect on smoking, then the instruments are invalid and the instrumental variables approach may yield misleading results.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] In this case, we would be mistaken to infer a causal effect of smoking on health from the observed correlation between tobacco taxes and health.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The strength of the instruments can be directly assessed because both the endogenous covariates and the instruments are observable.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] A common rule of thumb for models with one endogenous regressor is: the F-statistic against the null that the excluded instruments are irrelevant in the first-stage regression should be larger than 10.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] When the covariates are exogenous, the small-sample properties of the OLS estimator can be derived in a straightforward manner by calculating moments of the estimator conditional on *X*.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] When some of the covariates are endogenous so that instrumental variables estimation is implemented, simple expressions for the moments of the estimator cannot be so obtained.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Generally, instrumental variables estimators only have desirable asymptotic, not finite sample, properties, and inference is based on asymptotic approximations to the sampling distribution of the estimator.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] Even when the instruments are uncorrelated with the error in the equation of interest and when the instruments are not weak, the finite sample properties of the instrumental variables estimator may be poor.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The assumption that the instruments are not correlated with the error term in the equation of interest is not testable in exactly identified models.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] If the model is overidentified, there is information available which may be used to test this assumption.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The most common test of these *overidentifying restrictions*, called the Sargan–Hansen test, is based on the observation that the residuals should be uncorrelated with the set of exogenous variables if the instruments are truly exogenous.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] The Sargan–Hansen test statistic can be calculated as $TR^{2}$ (the number of observations multiplied by the coefficient of determination) from the OLS regression of the residuals onto the set of exogenous variables.
[src:econometrics/instrumental-variables-estimation] This statistic will be asymptotically chi-squared with *m* − *k* degrees of freedom under the null that the error term is uncorrelated with the instruments.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Some sources consider OLS to be linear regression.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Geometrically, this is seen as the sum of the squared distances, parallel to the axis of the dependent variable, between each data point in the set and the corresponding point on the regression surface—the smaller the differences, the better the model fits the data.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The resulting estimator can be expressed by a simple formula, especially in the case of a simple linear regression, in which there is a single regressor on the right side of the regression equation.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Under these conditions, the method of OLS provides minimum-variance mean-unbiased estimation when the errors have finite variances.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Under the additional assumption that the errors are normally distributed with zero mean, OLS is the maximum likelihood estimator that outperforms any non-linear unbiased estimator.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Each observation i includes a scalar response $y_{i}$ and a column vector $\mathbf {x} _{i}$ of p parameters (regressors), i.e., $\mathbf {x} _{i}=\left[x_{i1},x_{i2},\dots ,x_{ip}\right]^{\operatorname {T} }$ .
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Typically, a constant term is included in the set of regressors $\mathbf {X}$ , say, by taking $x_{i1}=1$ for all $i=1,\dots ,n$ .
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The coefficient $\beta _{1}$ corresponding to this regressor is called the *intercept*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Without the intercept, the fitted line is forced to cross the origin when $x_{i}={\vec {0}}$ .
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Regressors do not have to be independent for estimation to be consistent e.g. they may be non-linearly dependent.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Short of perfect multicollinearity, parameter estimates may still be consistent; however, as multicollinearity rises the standard error around such estimates increases and reduces the precision of such estimates.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] When there is perfect multicollinearity, it is no longer possible to obtain unique estimates for the coefficients to the related regressors; estimation for these parameters cannot converge (thus, it cannot be consistent).
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] As a concrete example where regressors are non-linearly dependent yet estimation may still be consistent, we might suspect the response depends linearly both on a value and its square; in which case we would include one regressor whose value is just the square of another regressor.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In that case, the model would be *quadratic* in the second regressor, but none-the-less is still considered a *linear* model because the model *is* still linear in the parameters ( ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ ).
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] of n linear equations in p unknown coefficients, $\beta _{1},\beta _{2},\dots ,\beta _{p}$ , with $n>p$ .
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] (Note: for a linear model as above, not all elements in $\mathbf {X}$ contains information on the data points.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The first column is populated with ones, $X_{i1}=1$ .
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Only the other columns contain actual data.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] So here p is equal to the number of regressors plus one).
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] A justification for choosing this criterion is given in Properties below.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The matrix $\mathbf {X} ^{\operatorname {T} }\mathbf {X}$ is known as the *normal matrix* or Gram matrix and the matrix $\mathbf {X} ^{\operatorname {T} }\mathbf {y}$ is known as the moment matrix of regressand by regressors.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Suppose *b* is a "candidate" value for the parameter vector *β*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The quantity *yi* − *xi*T*b*, called the *residual* for the *i*-th observation, measures the vertical distance between the data point (*xi*, *yi*) and the hyperplane *y* = *x*T*b*, and thus assesses the degree of fit between the actual data and the model.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *T* denotes the matrix transpose, and the rows of *X*, denoting the values of all the independent variables associated with a particular value of the dependent variable, are *Xi = xi*T.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The value of *b* which minimizes this sum is called the **OLS estimator for *β***.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The product *N* = *X*T *X* is a Gram matrix, and its inverse, *Q* = *N*−1, is the *cofactor matrix* of *β*, closely related to its covariance matrix, *C**β*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The matrix (*X*T *X*)−1 *X*T = *Q* *X*T is called the Moore–Penrose pseudoinverse matrix of *X*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This formulation highlights the point that estimation can be carried out if, and only if, there is no perfect multicollinearity between the explanatory variables (which would cause the Gram matrix to have no inverse).
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *P* = *X*(*X*T*X*)−1*X*T is the *projection matrix* onto the space *V* spanned by the columns of *X*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This matrix *P* is also sometimes called the *hat matrix* because it "puts a hat" onto the variable *y*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Another matrix, closely related to *P* is the *annihilator* matrix *M* = *In* − *P*; this is a projection matrix onto the space orthogonal to *V*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Both matrices *P* and *M* are symmetric and idempotent (meaning that *P*2 = *P* and *M*2 = *M*), and relate to the data matrix *X* via identities *PX* = *X* and *MX* = 0.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *P* is the projection matrix and *s*2 is the sample variance.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *X*i is the *i*-th row of matrix *X*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The denominator, *n*−*p*, is the statistical degrees of freedom.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The first quantity, *s*2, is the OLS estimate for *σ*2, whereas the second, $\scriptstyle {\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ , is the MLE estimate for *σ*2.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The two estimators are quite similar in large samples; the first estimator is always unbiased, while the second estimator is biased but has a smaller mean squared error.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In practice *s*2 is used more often, since it is more convenient for the hypothesis testing.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The square root of *s*2 is called the *regression standard error*, *standard error of the regression*, or *standard error of the equation*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] It is common to assess the goodness-of-fit of the OLS regression by comparing how much the initial variation in the sample can be reduced by regressing onto *X*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where TSS is the *total sum of squares* for the dependent variable, ${\textstyle L=I_{n}-{\frac {1}{n}}J_{n}}$ , and ${\textstyle J_{n}}$ is an *n*×*n* matrix of ones.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In that case, *R*2 will always be a number between 0 and 1, with values close to 1 indicating a good degree of fit.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the data matrix *X* contains only two variables, a constant and a scalar regressor *xi*, then this is called the "simple regression model".
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This case is often considered in the beginner statistics classes, as it provides much simpler formulas even suitable for manual calculation.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In the previous section the least squares estimator ${\hat {\beta }}$ was obtained as a value that minimizes the sum of squared residuals of the model.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it is also possible to derive the same estimator from other approaches.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In all cases the formula for OLS estimator remains the same: ^*β* = (*X*T*X*)−1*X*T*y*; the only difference is in how we interpret this result.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] For mathematicians, OLS is an approximate solution to an overdetermined system of linear equations *Xβ* ≈ *y*, where *β* is the unknown.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Assuming the system cannot be solved exactly (the number of equations *n* is much larger than the number of unknowns *p*), we are looking for a solution that could provide the smallest discrepancy between the right- and left- hand sides.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where ‖·‖ is the standard *L*2 norm in the *n*-dimensional Euclidean space **R***n*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The predicted quantity *Xβ* is just a certain linear combination of the vectors of regressors.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Thus, the residual vector *y* − *Xβ* will have the smallest length when *y* is projected orthogonally onto the linear subspace spanned by the columns of *X*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The OLS estimator ${\hat {\beta }}$ in this case can be interpreted as the coefficients of vector decomposition of ^*y* = *Py* along the basis of *X*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This means that $\mathbf {y} -\mathbf {X} {\boldsymbol {\hat {\beta }}}$ is the shortest of all possible vectors $\mathbf {y} -\mathbf {X} {\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ , that is, the variance of the residuals is the minimum possible.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Introducing ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\gamma }}}$ and a matrix *K* with the assumption that a matrix $[\mathbf {X} \ \mathbf {K} ]$ is non-singular and *K*T *X* = 0 (cf.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Another way of looking at it is to consider the regression line to be a weighted average of the lines passing through the combination of any two points in the dataset.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Although this way of calculation is more computationally expensive, it provides a better intuition on OLS.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The OLS estimator is identical to the maximum likelihood estimator (MLE) under the normality assumption for the error terms.[proof] This normality assumption has historical importance, as it provided the basis for the early work in linear regression analysis by Yule and Pearson.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] From the properties of MLE, we can infer that the OLS estimator is asymptotically efficient (in the sense of attaining the Cramér–Rao bound for variance) if the normality assumption is satisfied.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] These moment conditions state that the regressors should be uncorrelated with the errors.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Since *xi* is a *p*-vector, the number of moment conditions is equal to the dimension of the parameter vector *β*, and thus the system is exactly identified.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This is the so-called classical GMM case, when the estimator does not depend on the choice of the weighting matrix.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Note that the original strict exogeneity assumption E[*εi* | *xi*] = 0 implies a far richer set of moment conditions than stated above.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In particular, this assumption implies that for any vector-function ƒ, the moment condition E[*ƒ*(*xi*)·*εi*] = 0 will hold.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it can be shown using the Gauss–Markov theorem that the optimal choice of function ƒ is to take *ƒ*(*x*) = *x*, which results in the moment equation posted above.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] There are several different frameworks in which the linear regression model can be cast in order to make the OLS technique applicable.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Each of these settings produces the same formulas and same results.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The only difference is the interpretation and the assumptions which have to be imposed in order for the method to give meaningful results.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The choice of the applicable framework depends mostly on the nature of data in hand, and on the inference task which has to be performed.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] One of the lines of difference in interpretation is whether to treat the regressors as random variables, or as predefined constants.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In the first case (**random design**) the regressors *xi* are random and sampled together with the *yi*'s from some population, as in an observational study.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This approach allows for more natural study of the asymptotic properties of the estimators.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In the other interpretation (**fixed design**), the regressors *X* are treated as known constants set by a design, and *y* is sampled conditionally on the values of *X* as in an experiment.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] For practical purposes, this distinction is often unimportant, since estimation and inference is carried out while conditioning on *X*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] All results stated in this article are within the random design framework.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The classical model focuses on the "finite sample" estimation and inference, meaning that the number of observations *n* is fixed.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This contrasts with the other approaches, which study the asymptotic behavior of OLS, and in which the behavior at a large number of samples is studied.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] To prove finite sample unbiasedness of the OLS estimator, we require the following assumptions.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Violations of these assumptions can result in biased estimations of ***β***, biased standard errors, untrustworthy confidence intervals and significance tests.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the strict exogeneity does not hold (as is the case with many time series models, where exogeneity is assumed only with respect to the past shocks but not the future ones), then these estimators will be biased in finite samples.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In particular, the standard error of each coefficient $\scriptstyle {\hat {\beta }}_{j}$ is equal to square root of the *j*-th diagonal element of this matrix.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The estimate of this standard error is obtained by replacing the unknown quantity *σ*2 with its estimate *s*2.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The *Gauss–Markov theorem* states that under the *spherical errors* assumption (that is, the errors should be uncorrelated and homoscedastic) the estimator $\scriptstyle {\hat {\beta }}$ is efficient in the class of linear unbiased estimators.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This is called the *best linear unbiased estimator* (BLUE).
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] in the sense that this is a nonnegative-definite matrix.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This theorem establishes optimality only in the class of linear unbiased estimators, which is quite restrictive.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Depending on the distribution of the error terms *ε*, other, non-linear estimators may provide better results than OLS.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The properties listed so far are all valid regardless of the underlying distribution of the error terms.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However, if you are willing to assume that the *normality assumption* holds (that is, that *ε* ~ *N*(0, *σ*2*In*)), then additional properties of the OLS estimators can be stated.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This estimator reaches the Cramér–Rao bound for the model, and thus is optimal in the class of all unbiased estimators.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Note that unlike the Gauss–Markov theorem, this result establishes optimality among both linear and non-linear estimators, but only in the case of normally distributed error terms.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The variance of this estimator is equal to 2*σ*4/(*n* − *p*), which does not attain the Cramér–Rao bound of 2*σ*4/*n*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it was shown that there are no unbiased estimators of *σ*2 with variance smaller than that of the estimator *s*2.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Moreover, the estimators $\scriptstyle {\hat {\beta }}$ and *s*2 are independent, the fact which comes in useful when constructing the t- and F-tests for the regression.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] As was mentioned before, the estimator ${\hat {\beta }}$ is linear in *y*, meaning that it represents a linear combination of the dependent variables *yi*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The weights in this linear combination are functions of the regressors *X*, and generally are unequal.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The observations with high weights are called **influential** because they have a more pronounced effect on the value of the estimator.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] To analyze which observations are influential we remove a specific *j*-th observation and consider how much the estimated quantities are going to change (similarly to the jackknife method).
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *hj* = *xj*T (*X*T*X*)−1*xj* is the *j*-th diagonal element of the hat matrix *P*, and *xj* is the vector of regressors corresponding to the *j*-th observation.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] From the properties of the hat matrix, 0 ≤ *hj* ≤ 1, and they sum up to *p*, so that on average *hj* ≈ *p/n*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] These quantities *hj* are called the **leverages**, and observations with high *hj* are called **leverage points**.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Usually the observations with high leverage ought to be scrutinized more carefully, in case they are erroneous, or outliers, or in some other way atypical of the rest of the dataset.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *M*1 is the annihilator matrix for regressors *X*1.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The theorem can be used to establish a number of theoretical results.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] For example, having a regression with a constant and another regressor is equivalent to subtracting the means from the dependent variable and the regressor and then running the regression for the de-meaned variables but without the constant term.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The least squares estimators are point estimates of the linear regression model parameters *β*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However, generally we also want to know how close those estimates might be to the true values of parameters.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In other words, we want to construct the interval estimates.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Since we have not made any assumption about the distribution of error term *εi*, it is impossible to infer the distribution of the estimators ${\hat {\beta }}$ and ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ .
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Nevertheless, we can apply the central limit theorem to derive their *asymptotic* properties as sample size *n* goes to infinity.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] While the sample size is necessarily finite, it is customary to assume that *n* is "large enough" so that the true distribution of the OLS estimator is close to its asymptotic limit.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *q* denotes the quantile function of standard normal distribution, and [·]*jj* is the *j*-th diagonal element of a matrix.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] These asymptotic distributions can be used for prediction, testing hypotheses, constructing other estimators, etc..
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] As an example consider the problem of prediction.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Suppose $x_{0}$ is some point within the domain of distribution of the regressors, and one wants to know what the response variable would have been at that point.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Two hypothesis tests are particularly widely used.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] First, one wants to know if the estimated regression equation is any better than simply predicting that all values of the response variable equal its sample mean (if not, it is said to have no explanatory power).
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The null hypothesis of no explanatory value of the estimated regression is tested using an F-test.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the calculated F-value is found to be large enough to exceed its critical value for the pre-chosen level of significance, the null hypothesis is rejected and the alternative hypothesis, that the regression has explanatory power, is accepted.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Otherwise, the null hypothesis of no explanatory power is accepted.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Second, for each explanatory variable of interest, one wants to know whether its estimated coefficient differs significantly from zero—that is, whether this particular explanatory variable in fact has explanatory power in predicting the response variable.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Here the null hypothesis is that the true coefficient is zero.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This hypothesis is tested by computing the coefficient's t-statistic, as the ratio of the coefficient estimate to its standard error.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] If the t-statistic is larger than a predetermined value, the null hypothesis is rejected and the variable is found to have explanatory power, with its coefficient significantly different from zero.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Otherwise, the null hypothesis of a zero value of the true coefficient is accepted.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In addition, the Chow test is used to test whether two subsamples both have the same underlying true coefficient values.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The sum of squared residuals of regressions on each of the subsets and on the combined data set are compared by computing an F-statistic; if this exceeds a critical value, the null hypothesis of no difference between the two subsets is rejected; otherwise, it is accepted.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In a time series model, we require the stochastic process {*xi*, *yi*} to be stationary and ergodic; if {*xi*, *yi*} is nonstationary, OLS results are often biased unless {*xi*, *yi*} is co-integrating.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] We still require the regressors to be *strictly exogenous*: E[*xiεi*] = 0 for all *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Finally, the assumptions on the variance take the form of requiring that {*xiεi*} is a martingale difference sequence, with a finite matrix of second moments *Q**xxε*² = E[ *εi*2*xi xi*T ].
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *Q* is a *p*×*q* matrix of full rank, and *c* is a *q*×1 vector of known constants, where *q < p*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] In this case least squares estimation is equivalent to minimizing the sum of squared residuals of the model subject to the constraint *A*.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] This expression for the constrained estimator is valid as long as the matrix *XTX* is invertible.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] It was assumed from the beginning of this article that this matrix is of full rank, and it was noted that when the rank condition fails, *β* will not be identifiable.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] However it may happen that adding the restriction *A* makes *β* identifiable, in which case one would like to find the formula for the estimator.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] where *R* is a *p*×(*p* − *q*) matrix such that the matrix [*Q R*] is non-singular, and *RTQ* = 0.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] Such a matrix can always be found, although generally it is not unique.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p01] The second formula coincides with the first in case when *XTX* is invertible.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The following data set gives average heights and weights for American women aged 30–39 (source: *The World Almanac and Book of Facts, 1975*).
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] When only one dependent variable is being modeled, a scatterplot will suggest the form and strength of the relationship between the dependent variable and regressors.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] It might also reveal outliers, heteroscedasticity, and other aspects of the data that may complicate the interpretation of a fitted regression model.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The scatterplot suggests that the relationship is strong and can be approximated as a quadratic function.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] OLS can handle non-linear relationships by introducing the regressor *HEIGHT*2.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Ordinary least squares analysis often includes the use of diagnostic plots designed to detect departures of the data from the assumed form of the model.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] An important consideration when carrying out statistical inference using regression models is how the data were sampled.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] In this example, the data are averages rather than measurements on individual women.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The fit of the model is very good, but this does not imply that the weight of an individual woman can be predicted with high accuracy based only on her height.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] This example also demonstrates that coefficients determined by these calculations are sensitive to how the data is prepared.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The heights were originally given rounded to the nearest inch and have been converted and rounded to the nearest centimetre.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Since the conversion factor is one inch to 2.54 cm this is *not* an exact conversion.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The original inches can be recovered by Round(x/0.0254) and then re-converted to metric without rounding.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Using either of these equations to predict the weight of a 5' 6" (1.6764 m) woman gives similar values: 62.94 kg with rounding vs.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Thus a seemingly small variation in the data has a real effect on the coefficients but a small effect on the results of the equation.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] While this may look innocuous in the middle of the data range it could become significant at the extremes or in the case where the fitted model is used to project outside the data range (extrapolation).
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] This highlights a common error: this example is an abuse of OLS which inherently requires that the errors in the independent variable (in this case height) are zero or at least negligible.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The initial rounding to nearest inch plus any actual measurement errors constitute a finite and non-negligible error.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] As a result, the fitted parameters are not the best estimates they are presumed to be.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Though not totally spurious the error in the estimation will depend upon relative size of the *x* and *y* errors.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] We can use the least square mechanism to figure out the equation of a two body orbit in polar base co-ordinates.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] The equation typically used is $r(\theta )={\frac {p}{1-e\cos(\theta )}}$ where $r(\theta )$ is the radius of how far the object is from one of the bodies.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] In the equation the parameters p and e are used to determine the path of the orbit.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] We need to find the least-squares approximation of e and p for the given data.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] First we need to represent e and p in a linear form.
[src:econometrics/ordinary-least-squares-p02] Furthermore, one could fit for apsides by expanding $\cos(\theta )$ with an extra parameter as $\cos(\theta -\theta _{0})=\cos(\theta )\cos(\theta _{0})+\sin(\theta )\sin(\theta _{0})$ , which is linear in both $\cos(\theta )$ and in the extra basis function $\sin(\theta )$ .
[src:econometrics/panel-data] In statistics and econometrics, **panel data** and **longitudinal data** are both multi-dimensional data involving measurements over time.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] Panel data is a subset of longitudinal data where observations are for the same subjects each time.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] Time series and cross-sectional data can be thought of as special cases of panel data that are in one dimension only (one panel member or individual for the former, one time point for the latter).
[src:econometrics/panel-data] A literature search often involves time series, cross-sectional, or panel data.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] A study that uses panel data is called a longitudinal study or panel study.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] In the **multiple response permutation procedure** (**MRPP**) example above, two datasets with a panel structure are shown and the objective is to test whether there's a significant difference between people in the sample data.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] Individual characteristics (income, age, sex) are collected for different persons and different years.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] In the first dataset, two persons (1, 2) are observed every year for three years (2016, 2017, 2018).
[src:econometrics/panel-data] In the second dataset, three persons (1, 2, 3) are observed two times (person 1), three times (person 2), and one time (person 3), respectively, over three years (2016, 2017, 2018); in particular, person 1 is not observed in year 2018 and person 3 is not observed in 2016 or 2018.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] A **balanced panel** (e.g., the first dataset above) is a dataset in which *each* panel member (i.e., person) is observed *every* year.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] Consequently, if a balanced panel contains N panel members and T periods, the number of observations ( n ) in the dataset is necessarily $n=N\cdot T$ .
[src:econometrics/panel-data] An **unbalanced panel** (e.g., the second dataset above) is a dataset in which *at least one* panel member is not observed every period.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] Therefore, if an unbalanced panel contains N panel members and T periods, then the following strict inequality holds for the number of observations ( n ) in the dataset: $n<N\cdot T$ .
[src:econometrics/panel-data] Both datasets above are structured in the **long format**, which is where one row holds one observation per time.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] where i is the individual dimension and t is the time dimension.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] A general panel data regression model is written as $y_{it}=\alpha +\beta 'X_{it}+u_{it}$ .
[src:econometrics/panel-data] Different assumptions can be made on the precise structure of this general model.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] Two important models are the fixed effects model and the random effects model.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] $\mu _{i}$ are individual-specific, time-invariant effects (e.g., in a panel of countries this could include geography, climate, etc.) which are fixed over time, whereas $v_{it}$ is a time-varying random component.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] If $\mu _{i}$ is unobserved, and correlated with at least one of the independent variables, then it will cause omitted variable bias in a standard OLS regression.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] However, panel data methods, such as the fixed effects estimator or alternatively, the first-difference estimator can be used to control for it.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] If $\mu _{i}$ is not correlated with any of the independent variables, ordinary least squares linear regression methods can be used to yield unbiased and consistent estimates of the regression parameters.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] However, because $\mu _{i}$ is fixed over time, it will induce serial correlation in the error term of the regression.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] This means that more efficient estimation techniques are available.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] Random effects is one such method: it is a special case of feasible generalized least squares which controls for the structure of the serial correlation induced by $\mu _{i}$ .
[src:econometrics/panel-data] The presence of the lagged dependent variable violates strict exogeneity, that is, endogeneity may occur.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] The fixed effect estimator and the first differences estimator both rely on the assumption of strict exogeneity.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] Hence, if $u_{i}$ is believed to be correlated with one of the independent variables, an alternative estimation technique must be used.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] Instrumental variables or GMM techniques are commonly used in this situation, such as the Arellano–Bond estimator.
[src:econometrics/panel-data] While estimating this we should have the proper information about the instrumental variables.
